## Local Variables

A **local variable** is any variable defined inside a block `{ }`. It comes into existence when the definition is reached and is destroyed when the enclosing block ends — this lifetime is called **automatic storage duration**.

Local variables have **block scope**: they are visible from their point of definition to the closing brace of the block that contains them. Code outside that block cannot see or name them. This pairs naturally with the compound statements covered in *Compound statements (blocks)* — every block creates a fresh scope.

### Nesting and Shadowing

Blocks can be nested, and an inner block can define a variable with the same name as one in an outer block. The inner definition **shadows** the outer one — the outer variable still exists but is unreachable by name inside the inner block. Shadowing is legal but almost always a bug waiting to happen; prefer distinct names.

### Define Variables Close to First Use

Unlike C89, C++ lets you define a variable anywhere inside a block, not just at the top. The modern idiom is to define a variable as late as possible — ideally on the line where you first have a meaningful value for it. This keeps scope narrow and makes the code easier to follow.

```cpp
#include <vector>

int main() {
    std::vector<int> scores{42, 17, 95, 63};

    int passing{0};
    for (const auto score : scores) {
        if (score >= 60) {
            auto label{score >= 90 ? "excellent" : "passing"};
            std::cout << score << " (" << label << ")" << "\n";
            ++passing;
        }
    }
    std::cout << passing << " of " << scores.size() << " passed" << "\n";
}
```

`label` is defined inside the `if` block — it only exists for the iterations where it is actually needed. `passing` is defined just before the loop because the loop itself is its reason for existing.

### No Linkage

Local variables have **no linkage**: the same name in two different functions refers to two completely separate variables with no connection. This is in contrast to names declared at namespace scope, which can have internal or external linkage (covered in *User-defined namespaces and the scope resolution operator* and upcoming linkage lessons).

Keeping variables local by default is the right habit — it limits the surface area where a variable can be modified and makes functions easier to reason about in isolation.

