## Using Declarations and Using Directives

When you access a name from another namespace, you normally write the full qualified form: `std::cout`, `std::string`, and so on. The scope resolution operator was covered in **User-defined namespaces and the scope resolution operator**. Two shortcuts exist that let you drop the prefix — but they come with real trade-offs.

### Using Declarations

A **using declaration** introduces a single name into the current scope:

```cpp
using std::cout;
using std::string;

int main() {
    auto items = {"apple", "banana", "cherry"};
    int i = 0;
    for (auto item : items) {
        cout << i << ": " << item << "\n";
        ++i;
    }
}
```

Only the names you explicitly list are pulled in. If another namespace also has a `cout`, there is no conflict unless you also write a using declaration for that one. This makes using declarations the safer of the two options.

### Using Directives

A **using directive** pulls in every name from a namespace at once:

```cpp
using namespace std;
```

This is what beginners often write at the top of every file, and it is the source of a class of subtle bugs. If the standard library adds a new name in a future version — or if you include a header that adds one — that name silently enters your scope and can collide with your own identifiers or with names from other namespaces. The compiler may resolve the ambiguity in a surprising way, or refuse to compile at all.

### Scope Matters

Both constructs respect normal block scoping rules discussed in **Compound statements (blocks)**. A using directive inside a function body affects only that function, which limits the blast radius considerably. Putting either construct at namespace scope in a header file is the worst possible placement: every translation unit that includes the header inherits the pollution, making it a global problem of the kind warned about in **Why (non-const) global variables are evil**.

### Practical Guidance

- Prefer explicit qualification (`std::`) in header files — always.
- In `.cpp` files, a using declaration for a heavily-used name is reasonable.
- Avoid `using namespace std;` at file scope in any serious code.
- `using namespace std::literals;` (or its sub-namespaces for `_s`, `_sv`, etc.) is a common exception because the operator suffixes it provides cannot realistically conflict with anything you write.

